         <abstract>
            <p>This critique of C. B. Macpherson's systematic political thought raises some general problems that are of concern to theorists. One is the charge that in succumbing to "sociologism" Macpherson neglects the autonomous role of theory and fails to give proper weight to the distinct impact of scientism and technology. The second problem arises mainly from Macpherson's treatment of scientism as a "superstructure" of possessive individualism. The author concludes that in failing to make proper allowance for the antihumanistic tendencies of technology, Macpherson's humanistic ontology may turn out to be less humanistic than intended.</p>
         </abstract>
